excerpt: A traditional, teak-wood Lanna-style house built on pillars in 1895, with historic furnishings.
detail_description: Baan Sao Nak is a historic teak-wood Lanna-style house built in 1895, featuring traditional furnishings and architecture. Restored multiple times, this remarkable structure stands on 116 wooden posts and once served as a resting place for important visitors to Lampang. The house reflects the influence of Burmese and Lanna architecture, showcasing the wealth of Lampang's teak barons.
name: Baan Sao Nak
address: 6 Rat Wattana, Wiang Nuea, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

excerpt: Extensive 13th-century Buddhist compound in Northern Thai Lanna style, with many temples & a relic.
detail_description: Wat Phrathat Lampang Luang is a remarkable 13th-century Buddhist complex located in the Lampang Luang Sub-District of Koh Kah District. It is renowned for its Northern Thai Lanna style and houses numerous temples, including one that enshrines a relic believed to be a hair donated by Lord Buddha. The temple's pristine preservation showcases exemplary Lanna religious architecture, with minor renovations maintaining its original style.
name: WAT PHRA THAT LAMPANGLUANG
address: 271, Lampang Luang, Ko Kha District, Lampang 52130, Thailand

excerpt: Vast, scenic landscape featuring mountains, forests, waterfalls & year-round hot springs.
detail_description: Nestled in a vast and picturesque landscape, Chae Son National Park is a haven of natural beauty. The park boasts mountains, forests, and stunning waterfalls, as well as year-round hot springs that are a major attraction. Visitors can immerse themselves in the rich forestland teeming with streams and wildlife. A highlight is the Chae Son Hot Wells, where natural hot water pools allow for unique experiences like boiling eggs or indulging in mineral baths.
name: Chae Son National Park
address: 343, Chae Son, Mueang Pan District, Lampang 52240, Thailand

excerpt: Guided tours of the creation process in a factory producing traditional, hand-painted rice bowls.
detail_description: Dhanabadee Ceramic Museum offers guided tours of a traditional, hand-painted rice bowl factory. Founded by Mr. Phanasin Dhanabadeesakul, it honors the family's forefather and showcases the legendary rooster bowl of Dhanabadee. The museum aims to conserve arts and culture while promoting ceramic knowledge for visitors interested in observing modern ceramic production processes.
name: Dhanabadee Ceramic Museum
address: 32 ถนนวัดจองคำ พระบาท ซอย 1, ต.พระบาท Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

excerpt: Ancient temple complex known for its diverse architectural elements, gold-plated spire & statues.
detail_description: Wat Phra Kaew Don Tao Suchadaram is an ancient temple complex in Lampang known for its diverse architectural elements, including a gold-plated spire and statues. The 18th-century temple once housed the famous Emerald Buddha before it was moved to Bangkok's Wat Phra Kaew. The golden stupa and an ordination hall with mural paintings showcase Chiang Saen architecture style. Visitors can also explore a classic reclining Buddha and a museum displaying Lanna artifacts.
name: Wat Phra Kaew Don Tao Suchadaram
address: 8G25+98J, Prakaew Rd, Tambon Wiang Nuea, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

detail_description: Wat Phra Chedi Sao, located in Lampang, is a stunning temple with a rich history dating back thousands of years. The main attraction is the massive central stupa surrounded by 19 smaller stupas, giving the temple its name which means "twenty" in the local language. The Lanna-Burmese style architecture and a 15th-century solid gold Buddha image add to its antiquated charm.
name: Wat Phra Chedi Sao
address: Ton Thong Chai, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

excerpt: Government-run elephant center offering rides, shows, handling classes & overnight stays.
detail_description: The Thai Elephant Conservation Center, located just a 30-minute drive from Lampang, is a government-run facility dedicated to the preservation and care of Thailand's elephants. Visitors can engage in various activities such as feeding and bathing the elephants, watching them create art, and learning about conservation efforts. The center also features daily elephant shows showcasing traditional logging techniques and painting demonstrations. Additionally, it hosts the annual Khan Tok Chang festival celebrating the cultural significance of elephants in Thai society.
name: Thai Elephant Conservation Center
address: 964R+QW9, 272 หมู่ 6, Wiang Tan, Hang Chat District, Lampang 52190, Thailand

excerpt: Lampang, also called Nakhon Lampang to differentiate from Lampang province, is the third largest city in northern Thailand and capital of Lampang province and the Mueang Lampang district. Traditional names for Lampang include Wiang Lakon and Khelang Nakhon. The city is a trading and transportation center. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Lampang, also known as Nakhon Lampang, is the charming third largest city in northern Thailand and serves as the capital of Lampang province. It's a historical trading and transportation center with traditional names like Wiang Lakon and Khelang Nakhon. Despite being off the beaten path for many international tourists, visitors are often delighted by its intriguing tourist attractions.
name: Lampang
address: Mueang Lampang District, Lampang, Thailand

detail_description: Nestled along the serene banks of the Wang River, Wat Pong Sanuk Nua is a captivating temple complex that beautifully marries history with stunning architecture. This ancient site, built in the late 19th century, showcases an exquisite blend of Lanna and Shan styles, highlighted by its remarkable Hall of a Thousand Buddhas. Here, visitors can marvel at four seated Buddha statues and an impressive collection of 1,080 votive tablets housed within a charming open-air wooden structure.
name: Wat Pong Sanuk Nua
address: 60 Pong Sanuk Rd, Tambon Wiang Nuea, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

excerpt: Hikes through rainforest to cliffside caves with dramatic limestone stalactites & stalagmites.
detail_description: Tham Pha Thai National Park, located about 60 kilometers south of Lampang, Thailand, is a breathtaking natural attraction that draws visitors with its stunning limestone cave system. The park offers an opportunity to explore rainforest hikes leading to cliffside caves adorned with dramatic stalactites and stalagmites. One of the unique aspects of this park is the free admission for all visitors.
name: Tham Pha Thai National Park
address: Moo 3,, Ban Huat, Ngao District, Lampang 52110, Thailand

detail_description: Kad Kong Ta Walking Street in Lampang, also known as Talat Chin or Trok Talat Chin Rim Nam, is a historic market area located along the Wang River. The street comes alive every Saturday and Sunday on Talad Kao Street, offering a vintage atmosphere with over 100-year-old buildings lining the route. Visitors can explore the old market area and shop for local goods, souvenirs, and delicious food while experiencing the charm of traditional Thai houses and numerous shops and restaurants.
name: kad kong ta walking street Lampang
address: 7FRW+4Q6, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52100, Thailand

detail_description: Lampang, located southeast of Chiang Mai, is renowned for its iconic horse-drawn carriages. Visitors are encouraged to take a leisurely tour around the peaceful city on these charming carriages. The service typically offers small rounds for 200 baht, large rounds for 300 baht, and an hour-long ride for 500 baht. The starting point is in front of Thip Chang Hotel with morning departures at 10:00 a.m.
name: Horse-Drawn Carriages
address: 7FQQ+P49, Tambon Sop Tui, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52100, Thailand

excerpt: Chiang Mai is a city in mountainous northern Thailand. Founded in 1296, it was capital of the independent Lanna Kingdom until 1558. Its Old City area still retains vestiges of walls and moats from its history as a cultural and religious center. It’s also home to hundreds of elaborate Buddhist temples, including 14th-century Wat Phra Singh and 15th-century Wat Chedi Luang, adorned with carved serpents.
detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque mountains of northern Thailand, Chiang Mai is a city steeped in rich history and culture. Established in 1296, it served as the capital of the Lanna Kingdom until 1558. The Old City area still showcases remnants of its past, with ancient walls and moats that speak to its significance as a cultural hub.
name: Chiang Mai
address: Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai, Thailand

detail_description: Wat Chiang Rai is a stunning temple located in Lampang city, known for its striking white exterior reminiscent of the famous temple near Chiang Rai. The temple features intricate details such as glistening golden elements, sparkling gemstones, and dragon motifs. Visitors are advised to explore the temple both during the day and at night when it is beautifully illuminated. While smaller than its namesake, this replica offers a beautiful and easily accessible attraction in Lampang.
name: Wat Chiang Rai
address: 427 Tipchang Rd, Suan Dok, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52100, Thailand

excerpt: Lampang is a mountainous province in northern Thailand, east of Chiang Mai. It's an important center for ceramics and is known for Buddhist temples built during the Lanna era, which dates back to the 13th century. The province's capital, also called Lampang, features horse-drawn carriages. In the city center, Ban Sao Nak, a traditional teak house supported by pillars, is now a museum with antiques and gardens.
detail_description: Lampang, a province in northern Thailand, is renowned for its mountainous terrain and rich cultural heritage. The region is a hub for ceramic production and boasts ancient Buddhist temples dating back to the Lanna era. The capital city of Lampang offers a unique experience with its iconic horse-drawn carriages and the historic Ban Sao Nak, now transformed into a museum showcasing antiques and lush gardens.
name: Lampang
address: Thailand

excerpt: Vast multi-elevation park with forests, wildlife, flowers & Thailand's longest train tunnel.

One of its notable attractions is Thailand's longest train tunnel, which stretches 1.35km through tropical jungles. Visitors can explore bamboo forests, wildflower meadows, orchids, and lily flowers while hiking up one of the four mountain peaks within the park.
name: Doi Khun Tan National Park
address: Tha Pla Duk, Mae Tha District, Lamphun 51140, Thailand

excerpt: Open in the evenings, this lively weekend market offers a variety of goods & street food.

This vibrant market is steeped in history, reflecting over a century of trade with its charming blend of Chinese, Burmese, Western, and Lanna architectural styles. As the sun sets, the street comes alive with an array of stalls offering delicious traditional foods and unique handicrafts.

address: 7FRX+73V, Talad Gao Rd, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52100, Thailand

address: 7GW4+9JW, Wang Nuea, Wiang Nuea, Mueang Lampang District, Lampang 52000, Thailand

The temple is perched atop towering cliffs and features small white stupas that were meticulously crafted by hand. Visitors can ascend the 300-step staircase through a lush green forest to reach the temple, where they can partake in religious ceremonies and pay homage to the Buddha.

Visitors can explore various displays including trains and horse-drawn carriages while gaining a comprehensive understanding of the local communities and their significance in shaping the city.

excerpt: 14th-century Buddhist temple boasting gold & copper Buddhas, murals & ancient manuscripts.

The temple's main attraction is the Phra Phutta Sihing Buddha statue, which holds great cultural significance and is paraded through the city during the Songkran Festival.

The temple was established in the late 14th century on the grounds of a former royal flower garden. One of its most striking features is the impressive 48-meter-high bell-shaped chedi that enshrines sacred relics from Sukhothai.

address: 139 Suthep Rd, Tambon Su Thep, Mueang Chiang Mai District, Chiang Mai 50200, Thailand

detail_description: Doi Suthep is a 5,499-foot mountain in Chiang Mai, Thailand, known for its picturesque trails through evergreen forests and a hilltop temple called Wat Phra That Doi Suthep. The temple, coated in gold and nearly 800 years old, offers stunning views of the city below. It's a popular tourist spot, so visiting in the morning is recommended to avoid crowds.

excerpt: Bustling night market featuring street food vendors & local crafts, plus souvenirs.

The historic center is surrounded by monasteries and temples, with accommodations ranging from traditional homes to modern city hotels. The night bazaar, open from 18:00 to 22:30 daily, features an extensive collection of stalls and shops selling local crafts, souvenirs, street food, clothing, electronics and more.

The tour includes stops at famous stalls as well as hidden gems, with explanations of the dishes and opportunities to ask questions about the food.
name: Chiang Mai Street Food Tours
address: 266/42 Moo 3 4a soi 4/1, Ban Wang Tan, San Phak Wan, Hang Dong District, Chiang Mai 50230, Thailand

excerpt: Large zoo with many animal species, day & evening tram safari rides, kids' activities & shows.
detail_description: Chiang Mai Night Safari is a large zoo offering day and evening tram safari rides, kids' activities, and shows. The park features three major animal zones: Predator Prowl, Savanna Safari, and Jaguar Trail. Visitors can enjoy petting tiger cubs, hand-feeding wild animals, and watching dancing fountains and laser light shows. The Savanna Night Safari allows guests to see kangaroos, white rhinos, and water buffalos from an open tram.

address: 33, Nong Kwai, Hang Dong District, Chiang Mai 50230, Thailand

detail_description: Kew Fin is a stunning viewpoint located in the Chiang Mai province, offering a magnificent panoramic view of the surrounding mountains. It is said to have been a meeting place for opium traders in the past. Accessible via a steep road, it's recommended to have an experienced driver and suitable vehicle. The viewpoint can be easily missed from the main road due to its small sign. Visitors can park at the Doi Laan ranger stop and walk up 200m from the main road.

address: อุทยานแห่งชาติแจ้ซ้อน, Chae Son, Mueang Pan District, Chiang Mai 52240, Thailand

excerpt: Built as second center for the Sukhothai Kingdom around 1250, this city is now a historical park.
detail_description: Si Satchanalai Historical Park, established as the second center for the Sukhothai Kingdom in 1250, is a must-visit destination. It is part of the UNESCO World Heritage Site that preserves remnants of the Sukhothai Kingdom from the 12th to 14th centuries. The park features remarkable structures such as Wat Si Chum, Wat Maha That, and Wat Si Sawai.

Built between 1905 and 1912 by Burmese workers involved in the teak trade, this temple boasts intricate wooden details and ornate decorations. The interior features teak wood beams and ceilings, while the exterior showcases a Chedi and a large bodhi tree surrounded by small Buddha statues.

detail_description: Nhong Krathing Park is a spacious and inviting park with a clean and pleasant atmosphere. The park is family-friendly and even welcomes dogs. On weekends, visitors can find food vendors and occasional performances adding to the lively ambiance of this beautiful park in Lampang.

Established in 2007, it was the first zip-line ride of its kind in Thailand. The bases are situated atop towering trees, some reaching heights of 60-70 meters. Visitors can also walk across swinging suspension bridges at these impressive heights. The dish is topped with super-crisp, deep-fried egg noodles for added texture.
